EXP no: 11

AIM:
To write a C++ program to demonstrate function overloading of member functions, where multiple functions have the same name but different parameters in the same class.

ALGORITHM:
Start the program.
Define a class (e.g., Calculator).
Create multiple member functions with the same name but different parameters (number, type, or order of parameters).
In the main() function:
Create an object of the class.
Call the overloaded functions with appropriate arguments.
Observe that the compiler selects the correct function based on the arguments.
Stop the program.

PROGRAM :
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Calculator {
public:
    // Function to add two integers
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    // Function to add three integers
    int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }

    // Function to add two double values
    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }
};

int main() {
    Calculator calc;

    cout << "Addition of 2 integers: " << calc.add(5, 10) << endl;
    cout << "Addition of 3 integers: " << calc.add(5, 10, 15) << endl;
    cout << "Addition of 2 doubles: " << calc.add(5.5, 10.5) << endl;

    return 0;
}

OUTPUT :
Addition of 2 integers: 15
Addition of 3 integers: 30
Addition of 2 doubles: 16

RESULT :
The program successfully demonstrates member function overloading in C++, where multiple functions have the same name but differ in parameters, and the compiler selects the appropriate function automatically.
